deck_excerpt: DAD's home, and he brought snakes!
deck_description:
Ananta is a card that the moment I saw, I had to brew some kind of deck around it. Ultimately, the goals of this deck are quite simple, domino effect into getting a combination of Dark Armed Dragon and Ananta/Vaskii utilizing some straightforward combo lines. Until you get a hand that can do that (which can be turn 1 a surprising amount of the time), utilize the big booty of Reptilianne Gardna and the multiple sources of stubborn interaction this deck gains access to in order to control your opponent's ability to fight back. Also, be aware that the destruction effect on Ananta is not optional, so make sure that you have a second card you're okay with popping on the field if you set her up on turn 1 or if your opponent's board is clear.

The sideboard is mainly put together for your Zombie matchup, as Zombie World can be a nightmare to deal with as it completely shuts off Ananta. Fortunately, you do have main deck outs to the pesky Field Spell, as Vaskii only cares about the stats of what you tribute (which Dandylion sent off of Snake Rain/D.D.R. achieves quite nicely), and due to the lack of spells/traps that stick around on your side you can run a bevy of main deck backrow hate (Fun Tip: You can trigger your own Starlight Road using Heavy Storm if you wanna slam a Stardust Dragon on the field out of nowhere!). The D.D. monsters help with things like early Mezukis and Pyramid Turtles, and Nobleman just makes any defensive deck a minimal issue.

Any tips on how to improve this deck are greatly appreciated, thanks!

deck_excerpt: SPAM COUNTER TRAP HANDTRAP LIKE NO TOMORROW!!!
deck_description:
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon's incredible new support has come out in the TCG with Maze of the Masters and in Masterduel with Ultimate Sparkle, so I thought I would come up with a article on our favourite space-borne dragons! The new support for the strategy enables 1-card combos with Schwarzchild Infinity Dragon which is effectively full combo since it enables a summon of a rank 8 monster (with a XYZ dragon lock) without using up your normal summon! This card is effectively at 12 copies in the deck with maxxed out copies of Seyfert, Seventh Ascension, and the new Schwarzchild Infinity and Seventh Tachyon cards! Not only that, the generic rank 8 "Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion" adds any Tachyon or Galaxy card from deck on-summon! This enables Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon to pack 18 non-engine slots (21 if you include the Horus cards) making it capable of going 1st or second in Masterduel's cutthroat competitive ladder with handtraps/defensive staples! 
 
This insane consistency boost allows Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon to play to it's strengths, spamming its unique and insanely powerful countertrap "Tachyon Transmigration" and wielding ridiculously high attack stats (for ex. Draglubion with 17000ATK!)

 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon is composed of 3 archetypes which all lead to basically the same endboard. The deck is also consistent enough to maindeck 18 staples! 

The GALAXY-EYES TACHYON is composed of 23 cards. While it is two archetypes, they basically mesh together to form a singular cohesive strategy. The Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon deck core is composed of x3 Seyfert (deck's main normal summon), x2 Tachyon Cloudragon (the "poplar" of the deck), x1 Spiral Galaxy Dragon, x2 Dark End Evaporation Dragon, x3 Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal, x3 Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon (the main 1-card starter), x3 Seventh Ascension, x3 Seventh Tachyon and x3 Tachyon Transmigration. 
 
BYSTIAL cards count as handtraps and extenders for the strategy, and it also serves as good handtrap bait and breaks boards fairly easily since they're big beatsticks. It is composed of x1 Lubellion, x1 Magnamhut and x1 Druiswurm. 
 
This decklist has 15 STAPLE cards, thanks to the consistency upgrades the new Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon support cards offer. The handtraps amount to 12 in this deck and they are x3 Ash Blossom, x2 Imperm, x1 Nibiru, x1 Droll, x2 Maxx "C", and x3 Fuwalos. The last three staples are defensive cards, which are x2 Called By and x1 Crossout.
 
I chose to run maximum copies of Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal rather than the usual 1-2 copies since it searches for Tachyon Transmigration, this deck's win condition. It's summon effect is a quick effect, so it can be used during your opponent's turn so you can play through Maxx C and Fuwalos! Not only that, it's an extender, so it's perfect for playing through interruption. The deck is 42 cards, so there is less chance of drawing into garnets like Galactic Spiral Dragon and Cloudragon.
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon has a relatively simple and straightforward gameplan - get two level 8 monsters in the field, then summon XYZ summon the new support Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion to further your plays. The endboard generally ends on Hope Harbinger's spell negate and the infamous ace-card of Tachyon Transmigration in-hand! If there are extenders, then the endboard may even have additional interaction like Photon Galaxy Lord's monster negate. 
 
Here is the standard 1-card opening combo for Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon: 
 
Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon = Tachyon Transmigration in-hand (Countertrap handtrap omni-negate) and Number 38: Hope Harbinger (spell negate). 
  1. Activate Schwarzschild Infinity Dragon and summon itself and Spiral Galaxy Dragon from deck.
  2. XYZ summon Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion. 
  3. On-summon, Dragluxion searches for Tachyon Cloudragon.
  4. Cloudragon activates its effect to summon itself from hand when added from deck to hand.
  5. Activate Dragluxion's effect detaching two materials to summon Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon from Extra deck and attach Galaxy Satellite Dragon to it.
  6. Tribute Cloudragon to summon Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal from deck.
  7. On-summon, Primal adds from deck Tachyon Transmigration.
  8. Summon Spiral Galaxy Dragon from the GY.
  9. XYZ summon Draglubion using Primal and Spiral Galaxy.
  10. Activate Draglubion's effect detaching Spiral Galaxy Dragon to summon Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy.

    If you have extenders, you can search for additional copies of Tachyon Transmigration for more omni-negates since it isn't once per turn! This deck also has a lot of gas, so it can power through interruption. Remember, two level 8s = full combo since you can summon Dragluxion!
Going second, you can summon Numeron Dragon and ONE SHOT KILL 17000ATK! Here is the basic combo:
 
Two level 8s = 17000ATK OTK! 
  1. XYZ summon Divine Golden Shadow Dragon Dragluxion using two level 8 monsters. 
  2. On-summon, Dragluxion searches for Tachyon Cloudragon.
  3. Cloudragon activates its effect to summon itself from hand when added from deck to hand.
  4. Activate Dragluxion's effect detaching two materials to summon Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon from Extra deck and attach Galaxy Satellite Dragon to it.
  5. Tribute Cloudragon to summon Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal from deck.
  6. On-summon, Primal adds from deck Tachyon Transmigration.
  7. Summon Spiral Galaxy Dragon from the GY.
  8. XYZ summon Draglubion using Primal and Spiral Galaxy.
  9. Activate Draglubion's effect detaching Spiral Galaxy Dragon to summon Numeron Dragon.
  10. Detach 1 material from Numeron Dragon to make it 17000 ATK. 
If your opponent was silly enough to leave even a 8000ATK monster on the field in attack position, you'd STILL OTK through it!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Remember the various "locks" when playing with this deck! Schwarzchild Infinity Dragon locks you into Dragon XYZ monsters for the entire turn. Number 97: Draglubion locks special summoning for the rest of the turn after it's effect is used.
  • I chose to run maximum copies of Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal rather than the usual 1-2 copies since it searches for Tachyon Transmigration, this deck's win condition. It's summon effect is a quick effect, so it can be used during your opponent's turn so you can play through Maxx C and Fuwalos! Not only that, it's an extender, so it's perfect for playing through interruption.
  • If you enter your battle phase with a Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon with Galaxy Satellite Dragon as one of it's materials, detach it, so you can boost your attack to 10700ATK!
  • When Khaos Starsource Dragon is banished, especially with Dark End Evaporation Dragon's effect, it can make your level 4 Dragon on the field level 8. Do this play when you have Seyfert or Cloudragon (both level 4s) on the field so you can go for rank 8 plays!
  • Seventh Ascension, Seventh Tachyon, Bystial Lubellion and Seyfert are excellent handtrap baits, especially if you have full combo (2 level 8s) already in-hand.
  • When you're destroying face-up cards on the field, you can overlay on top of any Galaxy-Eyes you control Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon to destroy 1 card. Then overlay again on top of Full Armor Photon Dragon Cipher Blade Dragon for another destruction!
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Kite and Mizar's Galaxy-Eyes cards certainly received a massive glow-up with their new support from Ultimate Sparkle and Maze of the Masters - but the question is, will it succeed in Masterduel ladder?
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Negate my effects or pop my backrow.  I dare ya
deck_description:
Kurikara works similairly to Kaijus as a DM, and i wanted to take advantage of the differences.

Theme: Punishing the opponent for playing the game

- One half of the deck focuses heavily on strong backrow cards that clear boards and deal heavy amounts of burn damage.  This hopefully incentivises the opponent to blindly pop your backrow and play into the second half of the deck

- The other half of the deck are cards that activate when destroyed by an opponents card effect.  As many relevant Waking the Dragon type effects that i can find and fit.  

- The third and smallest half of the deck is a mix of stall cards like the timelords, and draw power because this deck tends to lose card advantage veeerrrrryyyyy quickly and needs time to recuperate.
A mistake Syrus would be proud of

deck_excerpt: Pure Apophis Midrange, with a Dragon Ravine splash for resiliency and extension
deck_description:
There's a lot of buzz around the Apophis (Odion) cards, especially around possible supplemental engines to help you combo and break boards. I've heard most people talk about the Kashtira engine as the best option for a true one-card combo by going into Arsenal Falcon, making Romulus, and dumping Destrudo with Zephyros in rotation to make AFD and get into the new field spell. I think this avenue fails for a number of reasons, but most importantly:

 

1. It uses your normal summon anyway for Kashtira Riseheart, so you are unable to use Man with the Mark as a starter if you go for the Fenrir 1-card combo.

 

2. If you get interrupted on your Arsenal Falcon, or your Romulus, or even your Fenrir, you're SOL. If you don't have Called By/Crossout and they negate your Falcon, you have no follow-up beyond hard drawing Treasures of the Kings--which, if you did that, why are we bothering with the convoluted Kashtira combo anyway?

 

Obviously using Fenrir as a starter allows you to have a true 1-card combo--the material you start with gives you a line into Silhouhatte Rabbit without needing anything else in hand other than a discard to Ravine, but the inherent fragility and non-extensibility of this line makes me shy away from it.

 

However, by using a small Dragon Ravine package as a supplemental engine, we can achieve largely the same effect while also providing some much needed flexibility and resiliency to the main combo. Man with the Mark remains our primary starter, with Anubis and Small World as a way to search out. Iff they negate the Man with the Mark, and you have any of the five ways to get to Dragon Ravine (3x Remus, 2x Ravine), you can use Ravine to dump Destrudo and go into AFD using the Man with the Mark. This gameplan DOES still require you to have an extra card to set to trigger the Treasures of the Kings, but that can be solved with some clever deckbuilding to make sure you have enough settable cards to fulfill this requirement while maintaining a good core engine and non-engine base.

 

In addition, having so much access to Dragon Ravine means, even without Man with the Mark, starting with Ravine and any non-Tuner normal summon means you can go into AFD and Apophis combo WITHOUT using Man with the Mark. This line is obviously more fragile--but it also means more hands are playable, even with a solid number of hand traps. Because of this, we need our hand traps to be non-Tuners--which means no ghost girls or Effect Veiler. We also need our hand traps to be ultra-impactful. This deck has a hard time going second, so we need our non-engine to be solid board breakers or game-ending hand traps. For that reason, we're playing Fuwalos, Droll, and Nibiru. In order to maintain a high number of Spells/Traps to set alongside our Treasures of the Kings, we're playing Impermanence and Book of Eclipse, as we need these to be useful going second but also fine to set on our own.

 

The Book of Eclipse slot could also be used for Forbidden Droplet instead. However, I default to Book for a few reasons:

 

1. We're already so card hungry with Dragon Ravine as an extender and Small World as a searcher, that it can be difficult to even have enough material for Droplet to good work into an established board.

 

2. Book of Eclipse can actually be used as an insulator against targeted negation when attempting to resolve Man with the Mark or AFD--which is a resiliency we sorely need.

 

3. Book of Eclipse has synergy with the Trap Monster line-up. Pumping out our Trap Monsters to interrupt the opponent first and then following up with Book of Eclipse actually resets the Trap Monsters (as they have the text "It's still a Trap") to be used later. This is obviously win-more, but it means that, in an intense grind-game, it is not as much of a liability as it might otherwise be.

 

Finally, the addition of Dragunity Remus and the sculpting of our hand trap lineup means Small World can bridge any of our handtraps into either Dragon Ravine (through Droll->Mulcharmy->Remus or Mulcharmy->Droll->Remus) or an Apophis Starter (Droll->Anubis->Man, Mulcharmy/Remus -> Droll -> Anubis, Nibiru -> Anubis -> Man) or even Serket if Treasures search is Ashed (Droll/Nibiru/Mulcharmy -> Anubis/Man -> Serket). That means, even though it takes a card, we can flex our non-engine lineup into starters or extenders as needed.

 

The Apophis typical endboard is the following:

 

1. Silhouhatte Rabbit

 

2. Divine Spirit of Apophis

 

3. Statue of Anguish Pattern

 

4. Apophis the Serpent

 

5. 2x Apophis the Swamp Deity

 

 

 

This is around 5-6 pops and two mass omni-negates on the field. This is a suite of endboard interaction that is particularly potent in a format that relies on monsters either on the field or in banishment. Spot removal is at a premium, and this deck ends on basically all spot removal. This can be a problem against decks like Fire King that prefer to be destroyed, but it is possible to play around their destructions.

 

All in all, I'm very, very happy with list, and I invite you to try it out!

deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Smash-Ups
deck_description:
Unstoppable. Untamable. Unextinct.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon a $11.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: Dinosmasher's Fury. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer. (It is unlikely you will find this deck at MSRP any longer because it came out 7 years ago)

Deckmaster: Evoltile Megachirella 
Domain Restriction: FIRE // REPTILE // DINOSAUR // DRAGON 

List based on my https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/serpentine-sovereignty-464985, editted to have a larger focus on Dinosaurs with a measure for budget. 

To create this upgrade, please remove these 15 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: Dinosmasher's Fury (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: 2 cards of the included 41-card structure deck will be duplicates

  • ydke://gIbgBIwCIQEghvIA6hp9Ak1PuwBvz/EF65JMApOApAK/EfYEUku8AhT1JQIfq/EE+TLFAGzkBgFBIdICWXtjBAvqDQC5U+sCI9adAoD9GAAP6rMFk17HAeElbwL7u6gC!!o3iPAgUpeQMnOWwBD4MWAXkSDgXT8RgFMKAIA9HrPQDXQsUDEoJoAGDEDwAcHRMF6c1wAASPUwXqoDgC!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 52 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://orLXBYqA5wBjCTwDFhYEAQGuagTkTFkAei5lAGIkJQH3yPoBvadvAZqqBwNw/cgEfY19Auw6sgTCz8UCz2DjBUfltwOkObgDQPO7BQcbRwSdFnAFtxvpBEMlkAV8toYDiVcRAg31DAHghQcCf7PcAYe+bQExkUYC47AqA3jXfQX7bU0CPJusBPkQWAS7+qgA!3T/vA41YjALvdhoBalshAZONUwJsWNMDvbMWALvJfQSS+pQA08DYAitSnAVgtwkEmf+HBQch6QLF5yMF!ExLHAA==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Dino Beatdown
  • Recursion
  • Card Access

Reccommended Combo Guide:
Turn 1: 
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69226388

Turn 2:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69271471

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? 

- Turn 1 combo
- Refill XYZ materials
- Provide Ability to discard
- Access Dinosaur Engine ( Xeno Meteorus )
- Provide Spell/Trap destruction on demand ( Evolsaur Diplo )

Our deckmaster is surprisingly more versitile than they seem at first read. The ability to not only start our plays but continue to be extremely valuable throughout the entire game accumulates an unmatched advantage over decks with simple deckmasters. 

An underrated part of the deckmaster is access to Evolsaur Diplo, who destroys spells and traps on summon. Use this to destroy problematic floodgates or advantage generators. In addition, we regain this ablity once Evolsaur Diplo is shuffled back into deck by our recursion pieces.
Another target is Evolsaur Vulcano, which can immediatly resummon an evolsaur in our GY to make the Rank-4 Evolzar Dolkka.
Lastly, to synergize with the Dinosaur package, Evoltile Megachirella can summon Xeno Meteorus, destroying a monster summoned by Miscellaneousaurus and accessing synchro plays through that. 
  
The refill of XYZ material allows us to revive powerful XYZ monsters from the grave without losing access to their effects.
Many of our cards, like Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark  only have effects in GY, so Evoltile Megachirella's discard cost to activate its effects happens to be beneficial. 

In a deck like this, a deckmaster like Evoltile Megachirella provides extremely valuable consistency and deck functionality.

The Recursion

- Resummon Ogdoadics
- Return Miscellaneousaurus to the GY using Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark 
- Revive XYZ and Refill XYZ materials ( Evoltile Megachirella + Nephilabyss, the Ogdoadic Overlord )
- I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- , Dark Hole Dragon , Transcendosaurus Meteorus , Ragnaraika Selene Snapper 

This aspect here is the core of the deck. Every time we resummon Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant by Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light , we can add an Ogododic Spell or Trap. Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark and Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light are both able to activate effects to special summon themselves from the GY.

Each time we resummon Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark , we can another opportunity to use Miscellaneousaurus by returning it to GY from Banishment. Thus, we can summon yet another Dinosaur to the field every turn. 

I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- gets out of control very quickly with its ablity to resummon itself, destroy monsters, and increase its attack every turn. Given the plethera of powerful field spells people enjoy playing, this likely happens quite frequently.

Use Number 60: Dugares the Timeless and Nephilabyss, the Ogdoadic Overlord to revive Dragon XYZ from our GY, then refill their materials using the effect of Evoltile Megachirella.
Good Revival Targets: 

  • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon: Steals a monster
  • Galaxy Photon Dragon / Dinowrestler Pankratops: Pop a card
  • Ragnaraika Selene Snapper: Destroy 2 Spells/Traps 
  • Horned Saurus: Attack Directly
  • Archnemeses Eschatos: Boardwipe
  • Sauropod Brachion: Flip board facedown 
  • [Other Endboard Pieces/Negates/HighAtk]  

Our free summons will continue until time ends, and through that, we make sure we always end up ahead every turn rotation.

Dino Beatdown

- big monster (Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus)
- Search Field Spells ( Horned Saurus )
- Pop/neutralize monsters ( Ultimate Conductor Tyranno )
- Attack modification ( Dinomorphia Rexterm )
- Lasting staying power 

Dinosaurs are the second aspect of evolution for reptiles, and as such are much stronger and scarier. Our cards like Ultimate Conductor Tyranno can neutralize boards, Dinowrestler Pankratops can remove threats, and Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus becomes a pain for our opponents to remove. The fantastic aspect of this deck is its ability to access all of this through Misc!

As I’m sure you’ve noticed, we only have one Miscellaneousaurus. BUT we can access it multiple times using Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark returning Miscellaneousaurus to GY! As we continue to use Miscellaneousaurus, we increase the arsenal of things it can access, and thus gets more powerful

The combos are here:

Using Misc for baby, then NS Deckmaster for Xeno:
[Banish 2]: Summon Petiteranodon who can be destroyed by Xeno Meteorus (who is summoned by our Deckmaster)

Using Misc for Extra Deck plays (after reshuffling key pieces of combo):
[Banish 4]: Summon Evolsaur Lios or Kaitoptera or Dinomorphia Therizia to summon Evolzar Solda  or Horned Saurus or Dinomorphia Rexterm respectivly.

Example Combo for Turn 2 return Miscellaneousaurus to GY:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=1038951-69271471

The endboard monsters:

- Ultimate Conductor Tyranno // Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus 
- Dinomorphia Rexterm 
- Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll
- Evolzar Solda // Evolzar Dolkka 
- Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon 

Strange Stand-alone cards

These cards may seem off at first glance. Here are their reasons for inclusion in this deck:

  • Polymerization 
    Searchable through Kaitoptera and summons Horned Saurus which searches Lair of Darkness

  • Soul Release along with Gigantic Thundercross 
    Targets down opposing recursion engines
  • Alien Stealthbuster, I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- 
    Searchable through Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant, and the plethora of reptile GY senders, in addition to "A" Cell Recombination Device and Mysterious Triangle 

  • Frostosaurus
    The garnet nessisary for Xeno Meteorus to summon Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus
  • Pitknight Earlie
    Great card that is hard to fully remove from the field due to resummon when due by battle or card effect

Tips

  • You don't like your Ogdoadic recursion pieces getting banished from the GY, so chain a revival spell to the banish to deny that. As a bonus, you can still activate their effects on summon even if they aren't summoned by their own effect!

  • Horned Saurus can set a field spell from the GY as well as from Deck, so don't feel bad if you need to discard Lair of Darkness. Similarly, Kaitoptera can add Polymerization from GY, so Polymerization  can be discarded if need. 
  • Be careful not to overuse the deckmaster Evoltile Megachirella. Discard fodder and life points are both finite, and this deck does not have in-combo ways to efficiently generate more of either. There are a total of 4 targets you can reasonably summon using it.

  • Early access to Raika no Kurokamitsuki will ensure peace of mind against any continous spells/traps your opponent may attempt to keep around. This card can ensure consistant access to a spell/trap destruction effect by reviving itself from the GY. In a pinch, you can NS the deckmaster for fodder to activate its revival effect.

  • You will need to massively alter your combo lines if you draw Animadorned Archosaur. Perhaps try to access King of the Feral Imps to search Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant in that scenerio.  
    • If you draw Evolsaur Lios, Normal Summon Lios and proceed to combo normally. Since Evo-Singularity needs an "Evoltile" monster in GY to activate: at the end of the combo use Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll's to NS your Deckmaster.  
  • Between Lair of Darkness [ Horned Saurus ], and Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju [ Souleating Oviraptor ], this deck has plenty of accessible ways to remove threats that cannot be destroyed by card effects or targetted.

  • Leaning on your varied recursion pieces to play an attrition gameplan should be the overall goal. The boards that this deck can make are not impressive on their own.  

To Recap: 

Important Cards: Miscellaneousaurus , Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark , Ultimate Conductor Tyranno , Evolzar Dolkka 

Strategy Elevator Pitch: Keep summoning more and more Dinosaurs to brandish the might of the prehistoric!

Other considerations:
 Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, Galaxy Photon Dragon, Lavalval Chain, Planet Pollutant Virus, Bystial Magnamhut, Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy, Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames, Card of Safe Return, Reptilianne Ramifications, [Night Sword Serpent  ] , Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon, Jewels of the Valiant , Circle of the Fire Kings , Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag , Five-Headed Link Dragon , Salamangreat Almiraj , Reptilianne Vaskii , [Stardust Trail] , Lava Golem, Kurikara Divincarnate , Dinomorphia Rexterm , Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf , Ragnaraika Armored Lizard , [ Vanguard of the Underground Emperor  ] , Sacrifice Level-Up , Salamangreat Revive , Giant Rex , Supersoaring , Primite Howl , Xyz Revenge , Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring , Called by the Grave , Monster Reborn , Special Hurricane , Xyz Force , Soul Release , Book of Eclipse 

Before Time Had a Name, They Ruled the World.

NB: replace numbers protection with new and improved "XYZ Unbreakable Barrier" for the better Astraltopia search card. Dodododo Warrior with Dodododo Warrior (new), Goblindbergh with Gogogo Goblindbergh (new). Side deck in utopic future zexal also (new).

Strategic Summary:

Welcome back for the final CDP of the month, and this time we’re merging two Xyz themes into one cohesive strategy. First up is the Lyrilusc WIND Winged Beast theme, an archetype dedicated to R1NK Xyz Monsters and attaching a lot of material to Lyrilusc – Assembled Nightingale. Between Lyrilusc – Bird Call, Lyrilusc – Cobalt Sparrow, Lyrilusc – Celestine Wagtail, and Lyrilusc – Recital Starling, this theme has all of the consistency-boosters one could hope for, as you grab the specific pairings of monsters needed for combos. Beyond the OTK combo of a multi-direct-attacking Assembled for game, the Lyrilusc also have some neat tricks like the full-board monster negate of Lyrilusc – Bird Strike and the spinning of Lyrilusc – Ensemblue Robin. But where this theme shines is its ability to easily merge two Winged Beast Xyz monsters into one with Lyrilusc – Bird Sanctuary, empowering them to take on the world… or eat it, if you’re Epurrely Plump!

 

That brings us to our second theme, the Fairy Xyz archetype Purrely! The Purrely archetype uses two Level 1 monsters to faux-Xyz Summon out its R2NK Xyz Monsters, and once the R2NK amasses enough material, it can be upgraded to a R7NK boss. Do you see where I’m going with this yet? If not, the goal of this hybrid is to combine Lyrilusc Level 1s and leftover Purrely or Purrelyly from your Quick-Play Spell activations to make Lyrilusc Xyz Monsters, then transfer the Lyrilusc and its associated Xyz Material to a Purrely R2NK (after Reprodocus turns it to Winged Beast of course), giving you everything you need to make a R7NK Purrely boss. No strings attached, no hoops or multiple Quick-Play Spells needed. Besides, this also gives the deck the benefit of being able to run Harpie’s Feather Storm, giving your Expurrely Noir extra help in the control department going into their turn. Consume the power of the storm, with the Lyrilusc and Purrely themes!

deck_excerpt: Final Countdown Win ft. Royal Magical Library
deck_description:
Hey there! In this deck, we will win with "Final Countdown" using "Royal Magical Library". You heard me right, as I have done it previously in Panda-Tethys-Junk decks. So, it should be easy.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw your whole deck with Library. You can find it with "Seventh Tachyon" thanks to Number 104.

2) With Double Summon + Pendulum Summon + Trismagistus, make sure you have 3 x Level 4 monsters. Then, XYZ Summon Knight with these two and play Countdown + Barrier + Void.

3) Activate Knight to bring forth The World and choose the outcome as heads with Barrier to skip your opponent's turn at the cost of sending two of your monsters you control to GY. These will be remaining Level 4 monster and Knight.

4) With turn skipped via The World and Void sending your hand to the GY, you can summon Balerdroch + Cockroach forever for The World to skip turns until you win the duel with "Final Countdown".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Spellbook of Secrets" + "Spellbook of Knowledge" + "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR + 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

So, in total, you can save up to 300 SR and 390 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Jackpot 7 FTK ft. Iron Chain Snake + Machina Fortress
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will win with "Jackpot 7" thanks to interaction between Snake and Fortress, with the help of Chalice. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have sent Shamisen to GY and 3 x Jackpot 7 cards in your hand, Link Summon Saryuja but don't use Panda as material. Then, Special Summon Snake with Saryuja and Special Summon Fortress with its ability...

  • If your opponent went first and their side is full, use Coral/Wurm/Legatia to free up a space for Fortress later on.

2) Give Fortress to your opponent with "Shien's Spy" and play Chalice on Snake. Then, Special Summon Shamisen and Synchro Summon Smashtank with Panda + Shamisen.

3) Activate Smashtank to discard everything in your hand but 3 x Jackpot 7 cards. Next, use Snake to target on Fortress, which leads into your opponent discarding "Jackpot 7" by force via Fortress. Repeating it two more times lets you win with "Jackpot 7".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Formula Synchron" can be either found within "Evoked Dragon of Miracles" or "Stardust Ties" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!
